corporation.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A> at: 4/16/02 8:01:21 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 490<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 8:26:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bruce-reactor profit forecast raised $1 billion.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> it was clear that they would not be viable under a fair competitive system.<br><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Was it<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  truly</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> fair?  Would it be fair to say that stricter<br>regulations are in place for nuclear power plants compared to say coal<br>firing plants?  Could that account for a portion of the cost increase?<br><br>The TRIGA reactor design, although a research reactor has<br>'consistently turned a profit for forty years.'<br><br>Why are commercial reactors so expensive? What can be done to make<br>them profitable? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 9:16:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bruce-reactor profit forecast raised $1 billion.</span><hr size=1> The TRIGA is profitable to its MANUFACTURER, not the user.<br>A fleet of Lexus school buses would be very profitable to the Lexus company but, a disaster for the bus fleet trying to bid out its services.<br><br>As to strict regulations adding to the cost.. YES, that is the whole point. Each of these machines contain the equivalent of more than a thousand atomic bombs worth of fallout being contained in a core that would reach 5,000 degrees if not constantly cooled. A major release would kill up to a range of 100,000 or so people and contaminate thousands of square miles. <br><br>Millions of people live within just a few miles of a reactor. The expense of dealing with such an incredibly hazardous machine requires vast sums of material and money. <br><br>The failed economics of atomic energy is imposed by the needs of the TECHNOLOGY. <br><br>Why does an airliner cost so much money? Because it MUST in order to be safe. Exactly the same logic holds true for atomic plants, but on a vaster scale.<br><br>Every time the industry tried to cut corners, like the ridiculous pressure suppression containments of GE boiling water reactors (a failure in itself), it jumps out and bites you.<br><br>As an aside, coal plants are also economic failures, more so if proper pollution controls are used. <br><br>Neither technology is central anymore.<br> yale<br> <br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><b